    mechanism:
      "24-amino-acid peptide encoded within the **mitochondrial 16S rRNA gene** — the **first mitochondrial-derived peptide (MDP) identified** (Hashimoto 2001) and the founding member of the MDP class. The original discovery context is itself remarkable: Hashimoto and colleagues were screening for compounds protective against Alzheimer's-related neuronal death and identified humanin from cDNA library cloned from the brain of a long-term survivor of familial Alzheimer's — humanin emerged as one of the survival factors associated with disease resistance. The discovery established that the mitochondrial genome encodes peptide signaling molecules (not just ETC components, tRNAs, and rRNAs) and opened the broader MDP research field. Subsequent MDPs identified include MOTS-c (12S rRNA, 2015), SHLP1-6 (Small Humanin-Like Peptides, also from 16S rRNA), and others. **Mechanism — anti-apoptotic activity (the central effect)**: Humanin's most evidence-supported activity is **inhibition of Bax-mediated apoptosis** — Bax is a pro-apoptotic Bcl-2 family protein that translocates to the mitochondrial outer membrane to trigger cytochrome c release and apoptotic cell death. Humanin binds Bax directly (and binds the related BimEL protein) preventing translocation and apoptosis triggering. The anti-apoptotic mechanism is particularly relevant in (a) neurodegeneration contexts where neuronal apoptosis drives disease progression, (b) cardiac ischemia-reperfusion injury where cardiomyocyte apoptosis worsens outcomes, (c) age-related cell loss generally. **Mechanism — IGF-1 receptor binding**: humanin binds and activates the IGF-1 binding protein-3 (IGFBP-3) and modulates IGF-1 signaling. IGF-1 pathway effects on growth, metabolism, and aging are complex (excess IGF-1 signaling shortens lifespan in many model organisms; deficient signaling produces different problems) — humanin's IGF-1 modulation is part of broader anti-aging signaling. **Mechanism — receptor binding**: humanin binds to a heterotrimeric receptor complex including formyl peptide receptor-like 1 (FPRL1), CNTFR (ciliary neurotrophic factor receptor), and WSX-1 / IL-27R subunit. This trimeric receptor mediates humanin's broader signaling effects. **Mechanism — neuroprotection**: substantial animal model evidence for protection against Alzheimer's-related neurodegeneration, ischemic stroke, and other neurological insults. Humanin supplementation in transgenic Alzheimer's mouse models reduces amyloid pathology and improves cognitive function. **Age-related decline**: humanin levels decline with age in humans; centenarians and their offspring tend to have higher humanin levels than age-matched controls (Yen 2013) — an epidemiological signal that humanin levels correlate with healthy aging. **HNG / S14G-Humanin — the ~1000× more potent analog**: substituting glycine for serine at position 14 produces **HNG (S14G-Humanin)**, a synthetic analog with substantially enhanced potency and stability. HNG is the form most commonly used in research peptide and longevity-protocol contexts; native humanin's lower potency limits practical use at typical research-peptide doses.",
