      "Research peptide; not FDA-approved. Less commercially common than MOTS-c or SS-31 (smaller research peptide market). Reputable vendors typically supply HNG (S14G-Humanin) rather than native humanin due to potency advantage. Verify which form is supplied — native humanin and HNG have very different effective doses. Cost: ~$60–120 per 5mg HNG vial.",
    notes:
      "## Native Humanin vs HNG (S14G-Humanin) — The Practical Distinction\nNative humanin has limited practical utility at typical research-peptide doses due to its modest potency. HNG (S14G-Humanin) with the serine→glycine substitution at position 14 is **~1000× more potent** in standard cell-based and animal model assays. The HNG analog is what most research peptide vendors actually supply when listing 'humanin' — verify which form before dosing.\n\n**Equivalent dose comparison:**\n- HNG (S14G-Humanin) 2mg ≈ Native humanin 2g (impractical for native form)\n- Practical research protocols use HNG exclusively\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nHNG 2mg subQ 2× weekly × 8–12 weeks. Track: cognitive function (memory, focus, verbal recall — the cognitive-aging use case has the most evidence), subjective energy, recovery from neurological insults if relevant. Anti-apoptotic and neuroprotective effects accumulate over weeks; subjective response is often subtle.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Mitochondrial trinity:** MOTS-c 10mg 2× weekly (AMPK / metabolic) + SS-31 10mg 3× weekly (cardiolipin / structural) + HNG 5mg 2× weekly (anti-apoptotic / neuroprotective). The three MDPs address distinct mitochondrial mechanisms; combinations are mechanistically rational.\n\n**Cognitive longevity stack:** HNG 2–5mg 2× weekly + Lion's Mane 1000mg/day (NGF/BDNF — different cognitive mechanism) + Bacopa Monnieri 300mg/day + omega-3 high-DHA + B-complex (methylated forms) + creatine 5g/day + structured cognitive training. The anti-apoptotic mechanism layered onto neurogenesis (Lion's Mane), neurosteroid (pregnenolone), and cognitive supplements provides comprehensive cognitive-aging coverage.\n\n**Cardioprotection / cardiovascular context:** HNG combined with SS-31 (cardiolipin protection) + omega-3 + targeted cardiovascular pharmacology (statin/Lp(a) management as indicated) + comprehensive cardiovascular risk management.\n\n## The Anti-Apoptotic Mechanism — Cut Both Ways\nHumanin's central mechanism is inhibition of Bax-mediated apoptosis. This is beneficial in contexts where unwanted cell death drives pathology:\n- Neurodegeneration (neuronal apoptosis is the disease)\n- Cardiac ischemia (cardiomyocyte apoptosis worsens outcomes)\n- Age-related cell loss\n\nBut apoptosis is also a critical defense against cancer — cells that should die because of accumulated damage (DNA damage, oncogenic transformation, viral infection) get inappropriately preserved by anti-apoptotic interventions. Humanin's anti-apoptotic effects are not selective for healthy cells — the mechanism applies equally to cancer cells trying to undergo programmed death.\n\nFor users with active malignancy or significant cancer risk: coordinate with oncologist before using humanin or HNG. The mechanism could theoretically protect cancer cells from chemotherapy-induced apoptosis or from natural surveillance mechanisms.\n\nFor healthy aging users: the anti-apoptotic effect on healthy cells is the desired benefit; cancer surveillance mechanisms are not catastrophically compromised at typical doses; the centenarian-correlation epidemiology (higher humanin in long-lived populations) suggests net benefit for aging individuals without active cancer.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nLyophilized HNG typical 5mg vial. Reconstitute with 2mL bacteriostatic water → 2.5mg/mL working concentration. Subcutaneous injection (insulin syringe), abdominal or thigh sites, rotate. Refrigerate reconstituted product; use within 28–30 days.\n\n## Synergies\n**MOTS-c:** complementary MDP (metabolic / AMPK signaling vs Humanin's anti-apoptotic / neuroprotective). **SS-31:** complementary cardiolipin structural support. **Urolithin A:** mitophagy — recycling damaged mitochondria; works alongside humanin's anti-apoptotic effect on intact cells. **CoQ10/Ubiquinol:** ETC substrate. **Lion's Mane:** complementary cognitive mechanism (NGF/BDNF). **Pregnenolone:** complementary neurosteroid cognitive mechanism. **Omega-3 (high DHA):** complementary neuroprotection.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\n**Hashimoto 2001 (Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences):** foundational humanin discovery paper from familial Alzheimer's survivor cDNA library screen. **Yen 2013 (Aging):** epidemiological correlation of higher humanin levels with longevity in centenarians and offspring. Multiple subsequent Cohen-laboratory papers (USC) extended the mechanism. Human clinical trial evidence remains limited — research peptide use ahead of formal clinical validation.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized in animal models. Founding MDP discovery establishes academic credibility. Anti-apoptotic mechanism solid; neuroprotection in Alzheimer's models robust; centenarian epidemiology suggestive. Human clinical trial evidence limited; HNG analog has more research literature than native humanin.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: foundational MDP with solid mechanistic case; anti-apoptotic and neuroprotective evidence robust in animal models; centenarian epidemiological correlation suggestive of healthy-aging relevance. Anecdote: less extensive use than MOTS-c or SS-31 in longevity community (smaller commercial peptide market); subjective effects subtle (anti-apoptotic mechanism is largely silent); pairs with MOTS-c / SS-31 for mitochondrial trinity. Decision frame: foundational mitochondrial-derived peptide; the anti-apoptotic mechanism is mechanistically distinct from MOTS-c (metabolic) and SS-31 (structural); HNG analog provides practical dosing; cancer-context caveat is real and worth coordinating with oncologist for users with active malignancy or significant cancer risk.",
