      "Aromatic redox cofactor with vitamin-like properties (debated whether to classify as a true vitamin — humans don't synthesize PQQ but do require dietary intake; the criteria for vitamin classification have been argued for PQQ since the 1990s). Originally identified as a bacterial cofactor for various dehydrogenase enzymes, PQQ has substantial roles in mammalian biology including effects on mitochondrial biogenesis and neurodevelopment. Found in foods including: fermented soybeans (natto, tempeh), green peppers, parsley, spinach, kiwi, papaya, and many others — typical Western dietary intake is ~10–20mg/day primarily from vegetables. **Mechanism — mitochondrial biogenesis (the central longevity-relevant effect)**: PQQ activates **PGC-1α** (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma coactivator-1 alpha), the master regulator of mitochondrial biogenesis. PGC-1α coordinates expression of nuclear-encoded mitochondrial genes alongside mitochondrial-genome-encoded genes, enabling synthesis of new mitochondria. PQQ-driven PGC-1α activation produces measurable mitochondrial biogenesis in animal models — increased mitochondrial DNA copy number, increased mitochondrial mass per cell, enhanced cellular respiratory capacity. The mitochondrial biogenesis mechanism complements mitochondrial maintenance interventions: PQQ creates new mitochondria; Urolithin A removes damaged mitochondria via mitophagy; SS-31 maintains structural integrity of intact mitochondria; MOTS-c signals metabolic status. Combinations address different aspects of mitochondrial homeostasis. **Mechanism — redox cofactor**: PQQ is a remarkably stable redox-cycling compound, capable of catalyzing >20,000 redox cycles per molecule (vs ~4 cycles for ascorbate). This catalytic redox stability provides substantial cumulative antioxidant activity at modest concentrations. PQQ scavenges superoxide particularly effectively, and supports glutathione regeneration cycling. **Mechanism — neuroprotection and neurodevelopment**: PQQ is a cofactor for nerve growth factor (NGF) signaling and supports BDNF expression. Animal studies show neuroprotection against various insults (excitotoxicity, ischemia, oxidative stress). Rodent dietary deficiency studies produced reproductive and developmental abnormalities, supporting the vitamin-classification argument. **Mechanism — sleep architecture**: PQQ has demonstrated effects on sleep quality in human studies — improved sleep onset, deeper sleep, increased REM. The mechanism is incompletely characterized but appears related to mitochondrial / metabolic effects on circadian biology. **Pharmacokinetics**: oral PQQ is reasonably bioavailable (~25–30%). The disodium salt form (PQQ disodium / BioPQQ) is the standard supplement format. Half-life moderate.",
