    notes:
      "## PQQ + CoQ10 — The Classic Mitochondrial Pairing\nPQQ and CoQ10 work via complementary mechanisms:\n- **PQQ:** mitochondrial biogenesis (creates new mitochondria) + redox cofactor activity\n- **CoQ10/Ubiquinol:** electron transport chain substrate (supports function of existing mitochondria)\n\nThe combination is mechanistically rational and commercially common — Jarrow Formulas QH-absorb + PQQ, Life Extension Super Ubiquinol CoQ10 with Enhanced Mitochondrial Support (PQQ), and many similar combination products use this rationale. For users running comprehensive mitochondrial support: PQQ 20mg + Ubiquinol 100–200mg daily is the foundational pairing.\n\n## Beginner Protocol\nPQQ 20mg/day AM with food × 8–12 weeks. Track: subjective energy, exercise capacity, sleep quality (the most subjectively perceptible effect), cognitive function. Sleep architecture benefits often noticeable within 1–2 weeks; broader mitochondrial biogenesis effects on longer timeline.\n\n## Advanced Protocol\n**Comprehensive mitochondrial pillar:** PQQ 20mg/day (biogenesis) + CoQ10/Ubiquinol 200mg/day (ETC substrate) + Urolithin A 500mg/day (mitophagy) + SS-31 5–10mg subQ 3× weekly (structural / cardiolipin) + MOTS-c 10mg subQ 2× weekly (AMPK / metabolic) + HNG 2–5mg subQ 2× weekly (anti-apoptotic). The five-pillar approach addresses mitochondrial biogenesis, structure, function, recycling, and apoptosis-protection simultaneously.\n\nLayer with NAD pathway (NMN/NR + TMG + pterostilbene + trigonelline), senolytic class (fisetin/quercetin), Nrf2 activator (sulforaphane), foundational micronutrients (omega-3, vitamin D3, magnesium glycinate, B-complex methylated forms), and lifestyle foundation (structured exercise, time-restricted eating, sleep optimization).\n\n## Sleep Architecture — A Distinct Use Case\nThe Nakano 2012 study showed measurable improvements in sleep architecture (deeper sleep, increased REM, improved sleep onset) at 20mg/day. The mechanism is incompletely characterized but involves mitochondrial / metabolic effects on circadian biology. The sleep-quality use case is one of the more subjectively perceptible PQQ benefits — users seeking sleep optimization may find PQQ's effects more readily noticeable than the broader mitochondrial biogenesis benefits which are largely silent.\n\nFor sleep-priority users: PQQ 20mg AM (paradoxically — PM dosing may produce stimulating effect that disrupts sleep onset) combined with magnesium glycinate, low-dose melatonin, and standard sleep hygiene foundations.\n\n## Reconstitution + Administration\nN/A — oral capsule or tablet. AM dosing with food preferred. Modest stimulating effect for some users argues for AM rather than PM dosing despite the documented sleep architecture benefits.\n\n## Synergies\n**CoQ10 / Ubiquinol:** classic mitochondrial pairing (biogenesis + ETC substrate). **SS-31:** complementary structural support. **MOTS-c:** complementary AMPK / metabolic. **Humanin:** complementary anti-apoptotic. **Urolithin A:** complementary mitophagy. **NAD precursors:** complementary sirtuin pathway support of mitochondrial biogenesis. **Lion's Mane:** complementary cognitive (NGF/BDNF) — particularly relevant pairing given PQQ's NGF cofactor mechanism. **Magnesium:** complementary for sleep quality use case.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\nNakano 2009 (n=71 healthy older adults, 20mg/day × 12 weeks): improved cognitive performance, particularly attention and working memory. Itoh 2016 (n=41 older adults with cognitive complaints, 20mg/day × 12 weeks): cognitive function improvements, NIRS-measured brain activity changes. Nakano 2012 (n=17 stress-affected adults, 20mg/day × 8 weeks): improved sleep quality, reduced fatigue. Hwang 2020 (n=42, 20mg/day × 8 weeks): improved cognition in cognitive complaints. Animal model evidence robust for mitochondrial biogenesis mechanism.\n\n## Evidence Quality\nMechanism well-characterized in cell and animal models. Human RCT evidence emerging but smaller than for some longevity supplements. Sleep architecture and cognitive aging contexts have the strongest human evidence. Long human dietary exposure history establishes excellent safety baseline. The vitamin-classification debate remains unresolved but the biological role is established.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\nResearch: solid mechanistic case for mitochondrial biogenesis via PGC-1α; emerging human RCT evidence in cognitive aging and sleep contexts; long dietary exposure history provides safety baseline. Anecdote: subjective effects on sleep often noticeable; broader mitochondrial benefits largely silent; pairs naturally with CoQ10 in classical mitochondrial supplement combinations. Decision frame: foundational mitochondrial biogenesis layer in comprehensive mitochondrial protocols; pairs with CoQ10/Ubiquinol as the classical mitochondrial pairing; cost-effective addition to broader longevity stacks; the sleep architecture benefit is one of the more subjectively perceptible effects.",
