    route: ["oral"],
    mechanism:
      "Endogenously synthesized lipophilic quinone present in essentially all cells (the 'Q' refers to its quinone structure; the '10' refers to the 10-isoprene-unit side chain in the human form, distinguishing CoQ10 from CoQ9 and other species' variants). CoQ10 exists in two interconvertible forms: **ubiquinone** (oxidized form) and **ubiquinol** (reduced form, gaining 2 electrons + 2 protons = ubiquinol-H2). The reduction-oxidation cycling between these two forms is central to function. **Mechanism — electron transport chain function (the central role)**: CoQ10 is the mobile electron carrier between Complex I (NADH dehydrogenase) and Complex II (succinate dehydrogenase) at the upstream end of the ETC, and Complex III (cytochrome bc1 complex) at the downstream end. Electrons from NADH and FADH2 are transferred through Complexes I/II to ubiquinone, reducing it to ubiquinol; ubiquinol then transfers electrons to Complex III, regenerating ubiquinone. This electron shuttling is essential for ATP synthesis — without functional CoQ10, ETC electron flow stalls and ATP production drops. **Mechanism — antioxidant activity**: ubiquinol (the reduced form) is a potent lipophilic antioxidant, particularly effective at protecting cell membranes and lipoprotein particles (LDL specifically) from oxidative damage. Ubiquinol regenerates oxidized vitamin E (α-tocopherol) back to its active form, extending vitamin E's antioxidant effective lifespan. The antioxidant function is most relevant in tissues with high mitochondrial activity (heart, skeletal muscle, brain, liver) and in protecting circulating LDL from oxidation (relevant for atherosclerosis prevention). **Mechanism — endogenous synthesis declines**: CoQ10 is synthesized endogenously via the mevalonate pathway — the same pathway that produces cholesterol. This is why **statin medications, which inhibit HMG-CoA reductase early in the mevalonate pathway, also reduce CoQ10 synthesis** as an off-target effect. Statin-induced CoQ10 depletion is one proposed mechanism for statin myalgia, though the clinical relevance is debated. CoQ10 levels also decline with age — by age 80, levels in heart tissue may be 30–40% of young-adult peak. **Mechanism — beyond ETC**: CoQ10 supports lysosomal function, modulates uncoupling proteins, supports mitochondrial permeability transition pore stability, and has roles in cell signaling. **Forms — ubiquinone vs ubiquinol bioavailability**: standard CoQ10 (ubiquinone) has poor oral bioavailability (~3–5% absolute) due to poor water solubility and large molecular size. Bioavailability-enhanced forms address this: (1) **Ubiquinol (reduced form)** — improved bioavailability vs ubiquinone, particularly in older adults whose endogenous reduction capacity may decline; (2) **Solubilized/emulsified forms (Q-Gel, Q-Sorb)** — improved absorption via emulsification; (3) **Liposomal CoQ10/Ubiquinol** — premium absorption; (4) **Crystal-free/solubilized ubiquinone** — better than standard crystalline ubiquinone. Form selection matters substantially for clinical effect.",
